Coulombs Law of Electrical Forces



                  Coulomb&#039;s Law of Electrical Forces 



For charged particles that are smaller than the distance between them, the force between two charges varies as the product of the charges and inversely as the square of the separation distance. The force acts along a straight line from one charge to the other.
F_{e}= \frac{Kq_{1}q_{2}}{r^{2}} \hat{\textbf{r}}
where F_{e}=\text{the electrical force between the two charges, measured in Newtons}
K = 8.99 \cdot 10^{9} \cdot \frac{N*m^{2}}{c^{2}}
q_{1}=\text{the quantity of charge of one particle, measured in coulombs (C)}
q_{2}=\text{the quantity of charge of the second particle, measured in coulombs (C)}
r = \text{distance in meters}


1 C or 1 Coulomb is associated with 6.25 billion billion electrons. This is about the amount of charge that passes through a common 100-watt light bulb in a little over a second.
K is the electrical constant, and is equal to \frac{1}{4\pi \epsilon_{0}}
Where \epsilon_{0} is the constant for the Permittivity of Free Space, 8.85 \text{ pF/m}.
Multiple Charges
When there are multiple charges acting, we perform a simple vector sum as with any other Force problem:
F_{net} = \sum\limits_{i} K \frac{q q_{i}}{r_{i}^{2}} \hat{\textbf{r}}_{i}

Electric Potential Due To A Point Charge
Topic: Electromagnetism



                  Electric Potential Due to Point Charges 



Consider a single point Charge Q. The Electric Field due to this point charge is a symmetric E = \frac{1}{4\pi \epsilon_{0}} \frac{Q}{r^{2}}
The potential difference due to this field is V_{b} - V_{a} = - \int\limits_{r_{a}}^{r_{b}}{\vec{\textbf{E}} \cdot d\vec{\ell}} = - \frac{Q}{4 \pi \epsilon_{0}} \int\limits_{r_{a}}^{r_{b}}{\frac{1}{r^{2}}dr} = \boxed{\frac{1}{4\pi \epsilon_{0}}\left(\frac{Q}{r_{b}} - \frac{Q}{r_{a}}\right)}
If we let V_{b} = 0 at r_{b} = \infty, then potential difference at a distance r from a single point charge is simply V = \frac{1}{4\pi \epsilon_{0}} \frac{Q}{r}
This is sometimes called the Coulomb potential.




