Gas Laws
Boyle’s Law
There is an inverse relationship between the pressure of a gas and its volume, if the temperature and number of moles are held constant.
P_{1}V_{1}=P_{2}V_{2}
Charles’s Law
There is a direct relationship between the volume of a gas and its temperature, if the pressure and number of moles are held constant.
\frac{V_{1}}{T_{1}}=\frac{V_{2}}{T_{2}}
Gay-Lussac’s Law
There is a direct relationship between the pressure of a gas and its temperature, if the volume and number of moles are held constant.
\frac{P_{1}}{T_{1}}=\frac{P_{2}}{T_{2}}
Avogadro’s Law
There is a direct relationship between the volume of a gas and the number of moles of the gas, if pressure and temperature are held constant.
\frac{V_{1}}{n_{1}}=\frac{V_{2}}{n_{2}}

